div.p:
               “I thank you,” replied 
               I; 
               “listen, therefore, to the deposition that I have to make. It is indeed a tale so strange, that I should fear you would not credit it, were there not something in truth which, however wonderful, forces conviction. The story is too connected to be mis
taken for a dream, and I have no motive for falsehood.” My manner, as I thus addressed him, was impressive, but calm; I had formed in my own heart a resolution to pursue my destroyer to death; and this purpose quieted my agony, and 
               for an interval reconciled me to life. I now related my history, 
               briefly, but with firmness and precision, marking the dates with accuracy, and never deviating into invective or exclamation.
